<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,185,354]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,185,210]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Recognition.</emphasis>
In the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundbeck, W." box="[502,696,185,210]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" refId="ref7421" refString="Lundbeck, W. (1922) Diptera Danica. Part UI. Pipunculidae, Phoridae. Wesley, London, 455 pp." type="book" year="1922">Lundbeck (1922)</bibRefCitation>
it runs to Group VI couplet 5 lead 
<specimenCount box="[1084,1136,185,209]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" type="generic">
2 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lundbeck)" authorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" box="[1105,1136,186,209]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="merochaeta">
<emphasis box="[1105,1136,186,209]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">M.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</specimenCount>
merochaeta (Lundbeck), a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lundbeck)" authorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1921" box="[290,578,221,246]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prodroma">
<emphasis box="[290,437,221,246]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">M. prodroma</emphasis>
(Lundbeck)
</taxonomicName>
, which differs in having only 2 bristles on the notopleuron plus a notopleural cleft. In the key to the males of the British species (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[742,894,257,282]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref7235" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney, 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 193 lead 1, which sends one back to couplet190, lead 
<specimenCount box="[439,493,294,318]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" type="generic">
1 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fallen)" authorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1823" box="[462,493,294,317]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flava">
<emphasis box="[462,493,294,317]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">M.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</specimenCount>
flava (Fallén) but its hypopygium is very different. Etymology. Named after Anni Duedahl the owner of the 
<typeStatus box="[442,490,330,354]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
